00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:13.000
Yeah. So the main benefit for using, so I'll just talk about Streamlit first of all,

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:16.000
because I think that's probably one of the most popular ones.

00:25:16.000 --> 00:25:19.000
There are kind of different reasons for the different applications.

00:25:19.000 --> 00:25:26.000
So Streamlit, the main one is that Streamlit re-renders everything from start to finish all the time.

00:25:26.000 --> 00:25:31.000
So if I had this in Streamlit and I changed this slider, the whole script re-executes from the beginning,

00:25:31.000 --> 00:25:36.000
every single thing. And you can use caching or some other tools to try to mitigate that problem.

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:39.000
But in general, it's going to re-render everything.

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:46.000
Whereas with Shiny, when I make this change, the only thing that re-executes is this small bit of code.

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:51.000
So it means that as your application grows, it kind of naturally stays efficient.

00:25:51.000 --> 00:25:55.000
Whereas with Streamlit, as your application grows, you need to start manually getting involved

00:25:55.000 --> 00:26:00.000
with caching to sort of make sure that it doesn't just get really, really slow or difficult.

00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:03.000
And I think that creates a lot of complexity for the developer,

00:26:03.000 --> 00:26:11.000
because they're sort of managing performance or what we call control flow in a manual way,

00:26:11.000 --> 00:26:14.000
whereas Shiny is kind of handling that for you.

00:26:14.000 --> 00:26:20.000
For Dash, the main difference is that Shiny has server state.

