Or that is being called by a number of rendering functions.

00:36:20.000 --> 00:36:24.000
And this is, again, something that differentiates Shiny from Streamlit and Dash.

00:36:24.000 --> 00:36:27.000
Like, neither of these things is really possible in those languages.

00:36:27.000 --> 00:36:33.000
And what's important about it is that this kind of works well for this sort of simple thing.

00:36:34.000 --> 00:36:38.000
But imagine if you had, like, 100 components or more.

00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:41.000
And you're in a large multi-page application.

00:36:41.000 --> 00:36:51.000
Shiny being able to keep track of this computation graph means that that application is going to be very efficient.

00:36:51.000 --> 00:36:55.000
Because it's only going to re-render the parts of that thing that are kind of downstream of that graph.

00:36:55.000 --> 00:36:58.000
So it's similar to a makefile or if you've used a pipelining tool.

00:36:58.000 --> 00:37:08.000
Where it's just only calculating the things that it absolutely needs to calculate in order to give the user the updated components.

