00:38:54.000 --> 00:38:55.000
So this is a core.

00:38:55.000 --> 00:38:56.000
This is one of the big things.

00:38:56.000 --> 00:39:00.000
It's just like reactive calculations and rendering functions.

00:39:00.000 --> 00:39:04.000
And in general, you want to use these whenever you want the value of a function.

00:39:04.000 --> 00:39:07.000
So here we're doing some calculations.

00:39:07.000 --> 00:39:10.000
And the thing that we're interested in is the value that comes out of that.

00:39:10.000 --> 00:39:12.000
The return value of the function.

00:39:12.000 --> 00:39:16.000
So this should be using reactive calculations or rendering functions.

00:39:16.000 --> 00:39:23.000
Similarly here, like the thing that we're returning is the data set at the end of it.

00:39:23.000 --> 00:39:27.000
But what if you want to have so that's one class of things.

00:39:27.000 --> 00:39:29.000
Is this like reactive calculations.

00:39:30.000 --> 00:39:35.000
But there's another class of interactions that you want to have with your application that are called side effects.

00:39:35.000 --> 00:39:46.000
So for example, if I wanted to update this slider or I want to download a file or, you know, send a query to a database or something like that.

00:39:46.000 --> 00:39:49.000
Sometimes you want to have a button that you're clicking.

00:39:49.000 --> 00:39:51.000
And that button is not really returning a value.

00:39:51.000 --> 00:39:55.000
It's like doing it's creating some sort of side effect.

00:39:55.000 --> 00:39:59.000
So there's another pattern in Shiny for that.

00:39:59.000 --> 00:40:03.000
And to do that.

00:40:03.000 --> 00:40:05.000
Turn the right place.

00:40:05.000 --> 00:40:08.000
So we're going to add a UI action button.

00:40:08.000 --> 00:40:17.000
And this is going to be called ID reset.

00:40:17.000 --> 00:40:20.000
And reset filter.

00:40:20.000 --> 00:40:23.000
Okay, so we have this little button.

00:40:23.000 --> 00:40:32.000
And instead of using reactive calculation, we're going to use another decorator from the reactive module, which is reactive effect.

00:40:32.000 --> 00:40:39.000
This is what you want whenever you want to get a side effect of user action instead of the value.

00:40:39.000 --> 00:40:44.000
And you're still using a function definition here to decide to find what's going to happen there.

00:40:44.000 --> 00:40:47.000
But this can be this doesn't really connect to anything.

00:40:47.000 --> 00:40:50.000
So like here we were using filter data because we needed to call that function later.

00:40:50.000 --> 00:40:53.000
We're not really going to be calling this reactive effect.

00:40:53.000 --> 00:40:55.000
So by convention we use this sort of underscore.

00:40:55.000 --> 00:40:58.000
But you can use any function you like.

00:40:58.000 --> 00:41:01.000
And just to show you that this is actually working.

00:41:01.000 --> 00:41:05.000
This is a good practice whenever you're doing these types of reactive effects.

00:41:05.000 --> 00:41:12.000
Just to just check that in the terminal that things are working as you're expecting them to.

00:41:12.000 --> 00:41:18.000
So we have...

00:41:18.000 --> 00:41:20.000
Oh, and see it's not working as I'm expecting it to.

00:41:20.000 --> 00:41:25.000
Because I actually didn't tell this reactive effect what I should respond to.

00:41:25.000 --> 00:41:29.000
And the way I do that is I have this reactive event.

00:41:29.000 --> 00:41:39.000
And this just basically says like what is the thing you want me to watch to decide when I should run.

00:41:39.000 --> 00:41:41.000
So let's try this again.

