I have these bunch of different update functions that allow you to update other UI elements.

00:42:05.000 --> 00:42:15.000
So I'm going to need the ID of this function, this slider, which is mass.

00:42:15.000 --> 00:42:21.000
And then all you do is pass in the value that you want to update.

00:42:21.000 --> 00:42:24.000
So if I wanted to update the value here.

00:42:24.000 --> 00:42:26.000
But if I wanted to update the min or the max.

00:42:26.000 --> 00:42:33.000
So for example, say I had a dropdown and I wanted the slider to be based on some data relative to that dropdown.

00:42:33.000 --> 00:42:38.000
You can update sort of anything that you can put in the inputs for the most part you can update.

00:42:38.000 --> 00:42:43.000
Okay, so let's just take a look at how this works.

00:42:43.000 --> 00:42:49.000
So now if I make this change and then I hit reset, it goes ahead and resets the filter.

00:42:49.000 --> 00:42:56.000
And then importantly, when the filter is reset, all the kind of downstream things get recalculated properly.

00:42:56.000 --> 00:43:00.000
So this is the sort of second pattern.

00:43:00.000 --> 00:43:07.000
And one of the things that I think is really important that I've seen people get into trouble with before when they're first starting to learn Shiny.

00:43:07.000 --> 00:43:13.000
Is Shiny is a framework that rewards you for trusting that it's going to do the updating properly.

00:43:13.000 --> 00:43:18.000
So for the most part, your rule should be Shiny is going to handle updating things.

00:43:18.000 --> 00:43:22.000
And figuring out like when to update stuff and when to re-render things.

00:43:22.000 --> 00:43:27.000
All I need to do is follow these sort of patterns of making sure that I'm kind of linking inputs and outputs.

00:43:27.000 --> 00:43:35.000
And referring to the either reactive calculations or the input values.

00:43:35.000 --> 00:43:42.000
And then Shiny is going to handle how your application is going to flow and make sure that things are up to date.

00:43:42.000 --> 00:43:44.000
So you don't really need to do those manually.

00:43:44.000 --> 00:43:49.000
The one case where you do kind of need to do that sort of manual, like when this happens, do this.

00:43:49.000 --> 00:43:51.000
Is when you're looking for a side effect.

00:43:51.000 --> 00:43:56.000
For the most part, if you're asking for the value of a function, the return value of a function.

00:43:56.000 --> 00:44:00.000
You don't really need to think about how things are re-rendering or executing.

00:44:00.000 --> 00:44:08.000
The only time you need to think about that is when you're pressing a button or doing something else where you're actually asking for a side effect.

00:44:08.000 --> 00:44:10.000
And that's kind of one of the core things.

00:44:10.000 --> 00:44:17.000
I see a lot of people where they're trying to build a Shiny app basically by having a ton of reactive effects and reactive events.

00:44:17.000 --> 00:44:20.000
And manually updating this thing.

00:44:20.000 --> 00:44:27.000
So you would have a reactive effect that watches this input math and updates a bunch of values whenever that happens.

00:44:27.000 --> 00:44:29.000
And that's not how Shiny works.

00:44:29.000 --> 00:44:33.000
Shiny is a declarative framework where what you want to do is just sort of write your application.

00:44:33.000 --> 00:44:38.000
And assume that the framework is going to go ahead and do the right thing with all of your values.

