00:44:48.000 --> 00:44:54.000
Why do penguins.copy instead of df.penguins.loc?

00:44:54.000 --> 00:45:02.000
So the main reason is like so Python does something called like Python objects.

00:45:02.000 --> 00:45:05.000
Some Python objects can be modified in place.

00:45:06.000 --> 00:45:14.000
And what that means is that if I just referred to penguins or just df equals penguins and then ran this like filter.

00:45:14.000 --> 00:45:18.000
It would actually filter this object as well.

00:45:18.000 --> 00:45:23.000
So R has like what's called copy on modify for all values.

00:45:23.000 --> 00:45:26.000
Which means that when you do an assignment actually copies the data.

00:45:26.000 --> 00:45:33.000
So like filtering or changing the copy data won't change the original.

00:45:33.000 --> 00:45:35.000
But in Python that's not true.

00:45:35.000 --> 00:45:46.000
We have a really good it will cause a lot of problems for Shiny because you're referring to this penguins data a number of different places with a number of different reactions.

00:45:46.000 --> 00:45:51.000
And you can run into problems if you didn't realize that you were modifying the original one when you're doing it.

00:45:51.000 --> 00:45:56.000
So this like calling a reactive will do that copying for you.

00:45:56.000 --> 00:45:58.000
So that's another good reason to use it.

00:45:58.000 --> 00:46:07.000
So whenever you're in a place where you are actually modifying something and it's a mutable object you should copy it.

00:46:07.000 --> 00:46:10.000
And let me just find the mutability article.

00:46:10.000 --> 00:46:17.000
So here's more on this.

